Name: Belgium 10-year Government Bond Yield (With GFD Extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Dec 1831 To May 1987
Daily From Jun 1987 To Mar 2022
Metadata:
Sources: The Times, London (1832-1844), The Economist and Banker`s Magazine (1845-1898), Sidney Homer, A History of Interest Rates, Princeton: Rutgers, 1963 (1959-1910), INSEE, Bulletin Mensual Statistique, Paris: INSEE (1911-25), League of Nations, Statistical Yearbook, Geneva: League of Nations (1926-1945), Banque National de Belge, Bulletin (1946-)
Notes: When Belgium separated from the Netherlands in 1832, one-third of the Dutch national debt was transferred to Belgium and Belgium began issuing its own bonds. The Belgium 5% Rentes (BGBEL5-LO) are used from December 1831 to December 1844, the Belgium 4.5% Rentes (BGBEL45-LO) are used from January 1845 to March 1874, the Belgium 3% Bonds of 1874 (BGBEL374-LO) as traded in London are used from April 1874 to December 1890, the Belgium 3% Bonds of 1838 (BGBEL3-PA) as traded in Paris are used from January 1891 to December 1910, the Belgium 3% Loan of 1914 (Redeemable 1940) (BGBEL314-LO) is used from January 1911 to December 1929, the Belgium 7% External Bonds of 1925 due 1955 (BGBEL755) as traded in New York is used from January 1930 to December 1936, and the Belgian 4% Bonds of 1936 (Redeemable 1970) (BGBEL436-LO) are used from January 1937 to November 1965.
Belgian yields are available beginning in July 1930 using the 3% bond. No data are available from May through July 1940 and from September 1944 through May 1945 due to war and occupation. The 4% Belgian unified debt bond series begins in January 1939. No data are available for May through July 1940. Beginning in 1957, the series is for bonds with a maturity of 5-20 years, in 1964 for bonds issued after 1962 with a maturity of 5-20 years, from 1968 for bonds with a maturity over 5 years, and beginning in 1987, 10-year bonds.
